*****************************************************************
Welcome to GnuPG Shell, version 1.0!
*****************************************************************

GnuPG Shell is a graphical frontend for the GNU Privacy Guard 
(GnuPG, http://www.gnupg.org). GnuPG Shell can be used to 
encrypt, decrypt, and sign files, to verify signatures and 
to manage the private and public keys.

Copyright (C) 2007 Will Spencer

GnuPG Shell is distributed in the hope that it will be useful, 
but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty of
MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE. See the
GNU General Public License for more details.

Installation under a GNU operating system (such as GNU/Linux)
=============================================================

You need the GNU development tools plus the GTK+ library, version
1.3 or higher and wxGTK, version 2.8.4 or higher, installed on your 
system. Unpack the tarball, `cd' into the new directory, compile, 
and install GnuPG Shell:

    tar xvzf gnupgshell-1.0.0.tar.gz
    cd gnupgshell-1.0.0/build
    make
    su -c "make install"

In order to do anything useful with GnuPG Shell you also need the
GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG) installed - see http://www.gnupg.org.

Please report any problems to will.spencer@tech-faq.com.


Installation under MS-Windows
=============================
You need Unicode build wxWidgets framework 2.8.4 or higher and
registered WXWIN system variable witch path to wxWidgets directory

You need to compile GnuPG Shell sources. You can do it with
Microsoft Visual Studio 2005 or higher. In ./build directory
exists corresponding Microsoft Visual Studio 
solution - wxGnuPGShell.sln. Open it in Visual Studio and
build it. All binaries would be in ./bin directory.

In order to do anything useful with GnuPG Shell you also need the
GNU Privacy Guard (GnuPG) - see http://www.gnupg.org.

Have fun!
